n -- tThe Stepmother, the Foisted Poison and the Changed Will. Some preliminaries for pseudo-Quintilian, Decl. Mai. 2 and pseudo-Libanius, Decl. 49 -- tOmnibus patemus insidiis: elite vulnerability in Major Declamations 11 -- tTyrans et tyrannicides dans les Petites déclamations -- tBibliography -- tIndex rerum -- tIndex locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs a genre situated at the crossroad of rhetoric and fiction, declamatio offers the freedom to experiment with new forms of discourse. Placing the literariness of declamatio into the spotlight, this volume showcases declamation as a realm of genuine literary creation with its own theoretical underpinning, literary technique and generic conventions. Focusing on the oeuvre of (Ps)Quintilian, this volume demonstrates that these texts constitute a genre on their own, the rhetorical and literary framework of which remains not yet fully mapped. It is of interest to students and scholars of Rhetoric and Roman Literature.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 4aDeklamation. 4aLateinische Literatur. 4aQuintilian. 4aRhetorik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aLatin literature.  aQuintilian.  aRoman declamation.  arhetoric.1 aBernstein, Neil W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCappello, Orazio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorbeill, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinter, Martin T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinter, Martin T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela